<a name=175></a>
<table width=100%>
<tr><td colspan=2><font class="h2font"> TFN Reviews Star Wars TCG</font></td></tr>
<tr><td><font class="bfont"> DeckTech reports on Tue May 7 2002 </font></td><td align=right><font class="bfont"> SW:TCG</font></td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=2><font class="bfont"> <img src=/news/images/vader_thmb.jpg align=left><B>Star Wars Trading Card Game: A New Hope or A Phantom Menace? </B><br>
<br>
A review of the new Star Wars TCG from Wizards of the Coast, Inc.<br>
By Aaron Brogdon of theforce.net<br>
<br>
On December 28, 2001 an announcement was made that shocked fans of the much beloved Star Wars Customizable Card Game. Decipher, Inc. notified gaming fans that Lucasfilm had chosen to not renew their license to produce Star Wars CCG and other card games based on the Star Wars universe. Shortly after, it was confirmed that Wizards of the Coast, Inc. had been awarded the license and would be releasing a brand new game created by master game designer Richard Garfield, originator of the popular trading card game Magic: The Gathering and other games. <br>
<br>
Rumors had been circulating the net for months but the move was now confirmed, leaving devoted Star Wars CCG fans reeling. Fans' reactions ranged from passionately expressed outrage to reluctant acceptance. Other card game enthusiasts expressed a variety of opinions from hope to outright skepticism. While still others, an outspoken few, hailed the news of a fresh new game. But in the ranks of the vast silent majority most have adopted a "wait and see" attitude. <br>
<br>
No matter what their reaction, everyone seems to agree on one thing: Wizard&#8217;s of the Coast has big shoes to fill. <br>
<br>
When I first heard the news about the license, I was among those shocked, upset, and outspoken. As soon as I realized that being angry or upset would accomplish nothing, I decided to see what I could find out about this new game. After all, I am a Star Wars fan, and if there is a game based on Star Wars that is worth my time and hard-earned money, I wanted to give it a chance. Rather than allow my opinion to be clouded and controlled by emotion and controversy, I began to judge the game on it&#8217;s own merits. It was at this point that my whole perspective changed. <br>
<br>
My path to learning more about the game has taken many twists and turns. Last week I had the privilege to sample the new game at Wizard&#8217;s of the Coast headquarters in Renton, WA. What I saw was a beautiful, fantastic and challenging game that delivers every bit of what it promises, and more. Simply put, it captures the essence of the climatic battles found in the Star Wars universe perfectly. I am confident that Star Wars fans of all ages will love the new Star Wars Trading Card Game. But the question on the minds of many is "Will it hold up in the eyes of hard-core gamers, especially those upset at the loss of Decipher&#8217;s Star Wars CCG?" After playing the game and seeing it in action for myself, my answer to that is "Yes, if they give it an honest chance." <br>
<br>
My review contains a basic summary of the game. More detailed information can be found in the rules, which you can find off of the SWTCG Main Page. The decks I played with were comprised of cards that will be released in the initial set, Attack of the Clones, and the first expansion set, Sith Rising. <br>
<br>
In the new Star Wars Trading Card Game.... <br>
<br>
For the rest of the in depth review check it out on theforce.net <A href="http://www.theforce.net/ccg/swtcg/swtcg_review.shtml" target="tfn">here.</A>  <br>
</font></td></tr>
<tr><td align=right colspan=2><font class="afont">  <a href=/send.php?di=/swtcg/index.php&id=175 target="_blank">send to friend</a> | <a href=/print.php?175 target="_blank">printer friendly</a></font></td></tr>
</table><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Hey, i read your full review at theforce.net.  Good review.  I found myself the same as you on many things.  Anyhow, I really like the speed aspect too, and really like the way small things like fighters can get shots in, and help you contest an arena until your bigger units come down.  A big ship may fire 7 dice at a fighter, but they can only kill one a turn!<br>
<br>
I really liked the battle cards and mission cards.  That's what lotr is missing, more surprises.<br>
<br>
Anyhow, very well written review</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Neal Razi</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> I understand that many people who are fans will want to look at it and maybe try a few games.  I for one have a major problem with any game where the outcome can be so randomized with dice.  I realise that this sight is very "WOTC Friendly" after Wotc supplied them so much prize support for their championship.  I have to say that I hope this game bombs the way I expect it to.  After six years and several thousand dollars invested, I am saddened if any real SWCCG player picks up this game.  <br>
<br>
What makes this game and WOTC even worse is the fact that WOTC and it's distributors threatened several stores telling them that if they wanted to receive their magic shippment they "would" order this game.  If the game does ok on its own merits great, but to have to threaten stores into selling it.  This stinks.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Alan Denny</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> SWTCG does not live up to SWCCG in the slightest. I believe WOTC totally missed the point, unless the point was to just make a game and slap the Star Wars franchise on it. What I believe was so universally loved about the SWCCG was the interaction between people, places, and things. Sure, the rules may have been complicated at times but where else could you have slapped trained Yoda to pilot Red 5 with a non-descript R2 droid and gone on an attack run? In SWTCG, that scenario or any like it are virtually impossible. The dice mechanic also reduces the new game to a crap shoot. Another complaint I have is if Attack of the Clones is the newest movie, how come WOTC could only get grainy, unclear pictures to put on their cards?  Decipher produced beautiful cards with pictures taken more than 20 years ago.  In the end, it seems they sucked the life out of SWCCG to come up with SWTCG.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Erik Lopez</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Don't even compare LotR with this game.<br>
LotR has more "surprises" and strategy in the Fellowship of the Ring set than SWTCG will have by the time it has run it's course.  <br>
You still have to try and make it sound better than SWCCG, why don't you work on one thing at a time...</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> John Noonan</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Who said it was better than SW:CCG? I agree with neal though lotr doesn't have to many suprises, it's basicly the same time and again. </font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> David Akers</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> As opposed to what?  The incredible versitility of SWTCG??  I just don't want anyone trying to drag LotR down to the level of SWTCG, that's all...</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> John Noonan</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> I don't think many people play that many suprises on the fellowship side of lords. People noticed that it clogs hand and screws up the cycling. I actually enjoyed other games where there are suprises. This game has them. The best reason not to play that people can come up with are all the same. It isn't decipher run, it isn't swccg, it has dice. The dice are a key part of the game. Just sit down learn the game, and then tell me it sucks. Oh on a side note, if anyone has the foil padme d version i would be interested in it as it is all i need for my set of foil padme's.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Robert Hendon</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> I did sit down, I did learn the game, I'm telling you it sucks...<br>
<br>
It's along the level of Young Jedi, I would like it too if I were 8 years old...<br>
Personally, I think that Garfield is a very capable game designer, I like the speed characteristic of the game...but it just doesn't compare with the elegance that I and many other SWCCGers have come to know and love...<br>
Sorry to burst your bubble, but I have a very open mind to any published card game...and I just can't get into this one.  <br>
If your only defense against the comments that this game sucks is that those comments come from closed mined people, or because it has dice and isn't decipher run, then maybe you are all too close-minded to admit that this game is lacking...</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> John Noonan</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> The only thing i see it lacking are people who will give it a chance. I personally didn't want to give it a chance either until I said what the hell I will buy it for the foil padme. Sure the picture sucked, but they could only do so much because the movie hasnt been released and they were only allowed to use certain pictures like lotr. I think this game has a chance to do well. sure it isn't complicated right now, but guess what neither is lotr. I could teach an 8 year old to play it. wait i have. Swccg wasn't that complicated at the beginning either. I bet when a few more expansions come out and you see that this game succeeds and people are enjoying, you will be kicking yourself. if it dies, oh well i spent less than a hundred bucks for cpl weeks of fun.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Robert Hendon</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Well, I finally did it.  Purchased a starter set and a few of the "mini-boosters".  I can pretty much admit to the same thing that the other general reviews have said--it's fun, and it's Star Wars.<br><br>That being said, I would beg to differ from those who would say that LOTR has no "surprises" or deep strategy;  to say so is clearly to indicate you have not studied the meta.  There's a wound management deck making the rounds that takes a rocket scientist to play properly but makes the Fellowship nigh invincible once it is going.  Strength of Kings remains a personal favorite of mine for the "denied" factor, and it's ALWAYS a surprise to see that coming (and cancel a Savagery or Battle Cry or other such nonsense).<br><br>But enough about LOTR.  We played a few games last night and there was a strategic element in "who hits who when, and which battle cards to use where".  I pulled a Jar Jar and a retreating Padme and I could definitely see the basis of a guerilla style deck in that vein.  True, there doesn't appear to be much room to add to this.  Basically it's a simplified war game which takes place in three arbitrary theatres (there's little flavor, for example, between space and ground units if you take away the pictures).<br><br>To summarize this brief review, I will add that while this game is not the devil incarnate, it truly isn't as deep as it needs to be and doesn't compare to the SWCCG (nor LOTR, for that matter).  That being said, it's a decent time waster, plays fast, and does give you the new characters to play with.  The best word I could think of to describe it was:  harmless.  Kind of like a "popcorn" movie--enjoyable, but it's not going to change the way cinema is viewed.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Kenneth Bradford</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Can you read, I DID give it a chance...<br>
And my argument isn't about simplicity of game mechanics...you seem to have missed the point.  The game is too static.  The only strategy choices you have is: hmmm...space, ground or character; should i use critical hit or damage prevention; duh, ion cannon looks like fun...<br>
C'mon, even the fan base is lacking due to the fact that it is heavily based in the SWCCG community, and most of us don't like it.  Unless the expansions expand game play immensely, and I mean with a capital 'I', this game will go nowhere...<br>
I mean, how can: "I think I'll fight in space and character arenas..." compare with "I'll base my deck around defending Kessel and Tatooine: Cantina to drain my opponent into submission."<br>
As Erik Lopez said in a past post here: 'you'll never see Yoda making an attack run in SWTCG'...You can't even put people in ships!...and if you could...Where would they go?!?<br>
It's the versitility that made the game, not the ease of teaching it to 8 year olds.......</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> John Noonan</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Don't worry, John Noonan, I will not compare SWTCG with LOTR.  Because I agree with David Akers and Neal Razi when they say that LOTR lacks surprises, and is basically the same thing over and over again.  SWTCG doesn't have any of the boring monotony that you find in LOTR.  I could easily have 10x more fun playing SWTCG by myself than playing LOTR in a 4-person multiplayer game.  Does SWTCG replace SWCCG?  No.  Does LOTR replace SWCCG?  Hell no.  Does SWCCG need to be replaced?  Not in my opinion.  The defensive shields in R3 fixed most of SWCCG's problems, and now that the new cards are FREE, there has never really been a better time to play SWCCG.  Anyone who quit because "the game is dead" just didn't look at the facts, because the game is better than ever.  But those people spread a "sky is falling" mentality that has caused the game to suffer greatly in a lot of areas, which is really too bad.  Those of us who are still playing regularly, know that there is no reason to stop.  Decipher still sends out prize support, still updates the ratings, and all the new cards are free.  What more do you want?  Anyway, I'm wondering whatever happened to Chu's comments on SWTCG.  I thought they were supposed to be put up on Monday???  </font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Brian Hunter</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> As usual, leave it to Brian to bring a voice of reason. SWCCG needs no replacement, because there is no valid reason for it to be looked at as a "dead game." But choosing which card game to invest in is obviously a matter of individual discretion. My experience with LOTR and SWTCG is limited, therefore, I'm in no position to offer any comparison. But I do feel that SWCCG certainly should not be perceived as something that is no longer an option.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Justin Warren</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Hey Brian Hunter...I know that someone like you thinks that when your opponent plays a card that increases his character's power by 2, you must be pretty surprised...<br>
The fact that you could have 10 times as much fun playing SWTCG by yourself...shows me that you must be easily amused...<br>
What were you trying to prove?<br>
I never once said that SWCCG should be replaced, I myself continue to play casually as I always have.  In fact, the majority of my posts here were meant to prove that SWCCG couldn't be replaced by the upstart SWTCG, and that SWTCG was a static, overly-simplified game.  If you don't care to read  what I have said, please don't post anything contradicting the three or four words you did browse over.<br>
Now, in-so-far as the same thing over and over again comment, please explain to me how SWTCG creates any sort of varied experience...even the possible deck designs seem dull and lifeless.  <br>
Let's analyze possibilities, SWTCG:  I will battle in space and/or ground and/or character arena.  LotR:  I will use twilight denial, I will corrupt the ringbearer, I will run to site 9, I will ambush my opponent, using archery, using high strength, powerful minions, many small minions, allys, ally killers, conditions, condition killers, strategic use of twilight, one or two, possibly more steps a turn, while using site control or throwing caution to the wind...by the way, how is your ion cannon doing...<br>
C'mon, I know you want to stick to anything StarWars related out of some life-debt to George Lucas or something, but a game like SWTCG doesn't deserve to be defended.<br>
Brian, get a clue...</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> John Noonan</font><font class="bfont"> - Tue May 7 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Hey John so you don't like the new game we all know it now. I happen to think it's a fun game that has a decent ammount of strategy. Nothing compared to SW:CCG of course but then again, the complexity of SW:CCG hampered it in some ways too. It is not for everyone, but a fair ammount of SW:CCG players should enjoy it if they give it a fair shot. Not all, but a decent number. As for lotr vs swtcg I don't really want to compare two drasticly different games, but they both have positives and negatives. Which is why we support both games here on the network, not every game is for every gamer. </font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> David Akers</font><font class="bfont"> - Wed May 8 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> I have to agree with John about LotR; it is an entertaining game with endless possibilities and not some static boring game where everything is predetermined from the start.  However, I must also agree with David that SW:TCG is going to be fun for some people.  I was an avid SW:CCG gamer and when I heard that Decipher had lost the license, I was one of the guys who chanted "down with WOTC!" and was ready to beat the doors down at their offices.  However, as I looked at the burning torch clenched in my fist, I realized "hey, it's just a card game".  SW:CCG was one of my favorite pasttimes, but it was not my life.  I still have my cards and play when I can, but I have since taken up LotR, not to replace SW:CCG, but as a separate experience.  As for the new SW:TCG, I don't plan on buying it for 2 reasons: 1)I really only have time in my life for one CCG, I've been trying to finish up my classes, plus I work 30+ hours a week, then I play paintball and just spend time with my girlfriend/friends.  So cards take the back seat.  2)I am broke as a joke and am barely able to afford LotR with car payments, insurance etc....  Therefore, I will not give SW:TCG the time of day, nor will I criticize it beyond the fact that it doesn't look too interesting to me with the dice and all, plus the memories of my beloved SW:CCG are still too fresh on my mind.  Anyway, SW:CCG is/was the best, LotR is tons of fun too, is not static, and I'm sure it will have more to offer and SW:TCG, well I just don't really have the time/desire to give it a spin.  </font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> will gilchrist</font><font class="bfont"> - Wed May 8 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> I wanted to reply to a few statements in various posts.<br>
<br>
1) Whoever said SWTCG does not have a fan base (or something to that effect) is dead wrong.  SWTCG Rebel Base opened around February.  By April 23rd, the game's release date, there were 80 members.  Now, just 14 days later there are 171 members on the site.  That is almost 7 a day. For every member there are probably 5-10 silent observers.  That is just one site right now.  There are also the countless players that don't even surf the web or got to message boards.  <br>
Now Decktech is going to do a site, and it has nothing to do with what some claim is WotC somehow bribing them or whatever the popular slander is.  It is because there are people out there that want a Decktech SWTCG site.<br>
All this in the face of intense opposition to this game.<br>
<br>
2) As for the statement that WotC threatened retailers with getting no Magic if they don't sell SWTCG; Where did that come from?  We all know many card shop retailers are not exactly fountains of knowledge.  I had one tell me that WotC was only selling it to superstores like WalMart and not to the little guy.  Then I went down the street to another small card shop and found it there.  He was obviously lying or confused.<br>
Even if it were true, it may just be a marketing strategy to get the game in stores since everyone is wary after Young Jedi and Jedi Knights had mediocre sales due to all the SW games on the market.  One shop didn't even know there was a new game or that the old was not being made anymore.<br>
<br>
3) For those saying it is too simple, that is the key to it's success thus far.  It has to start out user friendly to attract a new player base because they are targeting more than just current SW Gamers.  The press release made it clear they are seeking a bigger audience appeal.  We have been hearing hints the next sets will have more complexity and they should.  A guy at Celebration II WotC booth said in an article that will be posted on TFN later this week: "I was told by one of the game's creators that newer expansions to the game would feature more complicated rules and abilities."  Michael J Kent has promised more as well.  It is the nature of CCGs.  SWTCG has a great foundation that is inherently simple and easy to learn.  The complexity will be in the way you play it, using both the current and future sets.  No, it is not SWCCG and it will never replace it because it is so different in scope and gameplay, but like others have said, SWCCG is not dead anyway.<br>
<br>
4) And thanks to those who liked my review!  I honestly think that if people give SWTCG a fair chance, the majority of them will like it.  Of course not all will like it nor will all like it at the same level, because we all are different people.  This game will be successful.<br>
</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Aaron Brogdon</font><font class="bfont"> - Wed May 8 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Brian H remains of the coolest guys on DT.  That was hysterical.  His review is going to finish off the "big 6".  We delayed them for a few days because we had so many other announements.  That sadly is when the fun will end.<br>
<br>
To guys who get bent out of shape over swtcg: Did you ever think that it might be fun irritating you?  It's like making fun of the kid that spazzes.  You shouldn't do it, but you love to get the reaction.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Neal Razi</font><font class="bfont"> - Wed May 8 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Ok, I'm done arguing.<br>
<br>
The only reason I even posted anything on this article was due to Neal Razi's comment on LotR having no surprises, in comparison to SWTCG, which (I feel) has very little strategic backround.  This is my opinion, and I am entitled to it, as well as the right to voice it.  <br>
<br>
I personally don't care who thinks SWTCG is good, or why they like it.  <br>
<br>
If you like the game, by all means play it...just don't compare it to LotR...</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> John Noonan</font><font class="bfont"> - Wed May 8 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Noonan: I play lotr, ok?  yah, i play it a lot.  And it is almost surpriseless except for the occasional Power to Stat and Savagery.  That's my biggest complaint about it.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"> Neal Razi</font><font class="bfont"> - Wed May 8 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR> <font class="bfont"> Neal, stop spazzing...lol<br>
